\begin{remark}[Mathematical content of $W.\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$ and the stalks-level argument]
  \label{rem:W_IsMonoidal_content}
  Mathematically, $W.\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$ is the statement: \emph{if $L(f)$ is an isomorphism in $X.\mathrm{Modules}$, then so is $L(g \triangleleft f)$ for any presheaf of modules $g$} (and symmetrically for right whiskering). Concretely, $L(f)$ is iso iff $f$ becomes iso on each stalk (since sheafification is local), so we must show that $g \triangleleft f$ is stalkwise iso. At the stalk $x$, the presheaf tensor product computes as the $\mathcal O_{X,x}$-balanced tensor product $g_x \otimes_{\mathcal O_{X,x}} f_x$; tensoring with the identity on $g_x$ preserves stalk-level isomorphisms (since base change along a flat module factor preserves isos). The bookkeeping required is non-trivial because Mathlib does not yet expose the stalk-of-presheaf-tensor identification in the varying-ring case; the alternative routes (closedness via internal hom; \texttt{sheafificationCompToSheaf} to \texttt{AddCommGrpCat}-side $W.\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$) are both blocked because \texttt{MonoidalClosed} for \texttt{PresheafOfModules}\,$R_0$ is absent for varying $R_0$ and \texttt{toPresheaf}\,$R_0$ is not monoidal (it sends a ring-balanced tensor to a $\mathbb Z$-tensor, which differs). The gap therefore remains a named-deferred Mathlib gap-fill rather than a project-local proof obligation.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}[Honest disclosure: $W.\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$ is load-bearing post-C1]
  \label{rem:W_IsMonoidal_load_bearing}
  The status of $W.\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$ as a downstream dependency transitioned between Phase~C steps:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Pre-C1.} The gap was \emph{dormant}: no active proof DAG in the project consumed it. The earlier $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ was defined as the global-sections approximation $\mathrm{CommRing.Pic}\,\Gamma(X, \top)$, which factors through the affine ring-side Picard-group machinery and never invoked the symmetric monoidal structure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ at all. The instance was carried in the file purely to scaffold Phase~C step~C1.
    \item \textbf{Post-C1 (iter-109, Archon canonical).} The gap is now \emph{load-bearing} for the entire Pic-and-down arc. The C1 refactor sets $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X := (\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules})^\times$ (mirroring the ring-side idiom $\mathrm{CommRing.Pic}\,R := \mathrm{Shrink}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,(\mathrm{SemimoduleCat}\,R))^\times$), and the commutative-group structure on $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ derives from $\mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}$ via $\mathrm{Skeleton.instCommMonoid}$ and $\mathrm{instCommGroupUnits}$. The braided structure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ is itself transported through the \texttt{LocalizedMonoidal} machinery, which requires $(W\,X).\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$. Consequently every C1+ theorem about $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$, $\mathrm{Pic}\,X$, $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctor}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctorAb}$, the Jacobian instances of Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}, and the Abel--Jacobi map of Chapter~\ref{chap:AbelJacobi} (via $\mathtt{ofCurve}$) transitively depends on $\mathtt{instIsMonoidal\_W}$.
  \end{itemize}
  This is an honest accounting move, not a regression: $\mathtt{lean\_verify}$ runs on the post-C1 declarations surface $\mathtt{sorryAx}$ in their axiom chains, all rooted at the named-deferred gap in \texttt{Modules/Monoidal.lean}. The disclosure follows the same pattern as Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} in Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}: the project ships a framework whose end-state semantics are well-formed APIs conditional on a small, named set of Mathlib gap-fills, rather than concealing those gaps behind shallow surfaces. The gap-fill itself remains the stalks-of-presheaf-tensor identification in the varying-ring setting (Remark~\ref{rem:W_IsMonoidal_content}); no project-local lemma may bridge it.
\end{remark}

\section{Braided (symmetric) structure}

The symmetric structure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ is what enables the commutative-monoid structure on the skeleton of objects, hence the commutative-group structure on $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X = (\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules})^\times$ (Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}). It is recorded in two no-content registration steps, exposing transitively-existing structure rather than building anything new.

\begin{theorem}\leanok
[Symmetric structure on the presheaf side]
  \label{thm:Modules_BraidedCategoryPresheaf}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Modules.instBraidedCategoryPresheaf}
  For every scheme $X$, the category $\mathrm{PresheafOfModules}\,\mathcal O_X$ of presheaves of $\mathcal O_X$-modules carries a canonical \emph{symmetric} (in particular braided) monoidal structure with tensor product computed pointwise.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}\leanok
  Pointwise on each open $U \subseteq X$, the tensor product is the standard tensor on $\mathrm{ModuleCat}\,\mathcal O_X(U)$, which is symmetric monoidal (\texttt{Mathlib.Algebra.Category.ModuleCat.Monoidal}). The presheaf-level instance lifts this pointwise (\texttt{Mathlib.Algebra.Category.ModuleCat.Presheaf.Monoidal}), and the project simply transports the symmetric structure across the definitional equality $X.\mathrm{ringCatSheaf}.\mathrm{obj} = X.\mathrm{sheaf}.\mathrm{obj} \circ \mathrm{forget}_2\,\mathrm{CommRingCat}\,\mathrm{RingCat}$, mirroring the analogous monoidal-side bridging instance (Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}).
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}\leanok
[Symmetric structure on the sheaf side]
  \label{thm:Modules_BraidedCategory}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Modules.instBraidedCategory}
  \uses{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory, thm:Modules_BraidedCategoryPresheaf}
  For every scheme $X$, the symmetric monoidal category $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ carries a canonical braided (in fact symmetric) structure with braiding given by the standard tensor-swap, transported from the presheaf side through sheafification.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}\leanok
  \uses{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory, thm:Modules_BraidedCategoryPresheaf}
  The \texttt{LocalizedMonoidal} machinery (\texttt{CategoryTheory.Localization.Monoidal.Braided}) provides a braided structure on the localisation $L(\mathrm{PresheafOfModules}\,\mathcal O_X)/W$ whenever the source category is braided and the localising class $W$ is monoidal. Both inputs are in place: the presheaf side is symmetric (Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_BraidedCategoryPresheaf}), and $W$ is monoidal (the named-deferred gap $\mathtt{instIsMonoidal\_W}$ of Remark~\ref{rem:W_IsMonoidal_load_bearing}). The sheaf-side braiding is then the image under $L$ of the presheaf-side braiding, and its hexagon axioms transfer through the universal property of the monoidal localisation.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}[No new mathematical content]
  Both instances above are project-side \emph{registrations} exposing structure that is transitively present in Mathlib. They become important only at C1 (Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}), where the typeclass chain $\mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,X.\mathrm{Modules} \Rightarrow \mathrm{CommMonoid}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}) \Rightarrow \mathrm{CommGroup}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules})^\times$ is invoked to give $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ its commutative-group structure.
\end{remark}

